Imagine you go to a government office to get your passport stamped. You walk up to the clerk's desk. The clerk is fully prepared to do their 
job—they have their stamp ready, their ink pad open, and they look at you and say: 

"Please hand me your passport so I can stamp it."

You reach out your hand, but you are holding absolutely nothing. You are empty-handed. The clerk doesn't try to stamp the thin air 
(which would be a NullReferenceException). Instead, the clerk actively stops the process, looks at you, and rejects your request: 
"You told me you were bringing a document, but you came empty-handed. I cannot do my job with nothing, so I am halting this process immediately!"

In the programming world, a method explicitly rejecting an empty parameter before doing any real work is exactly what an ArgumentNullException is.

## The Technical Reality

Why do we have both NullReferenceException and ArgumentNullException? 

A NullReferenceException is considered a "messy" crash. It happens deep inside the code when the system unexpectedly hits a wall.

An ArgumentNullException, on the other hand, is a form of defensive programming. It is thrown intentionally by the author of a method 
(or by the .NET framework itself) to "guard the door." It protects the internal logic of the method from dealing with garbage data and 
provides a very clear, specific error message to the developer who called the method.

## Let's Look at the Code

public void MakeNameUppercase(string name)
{
    // If 'name' is 'null', the ToUpper() function cannot operate on non-existent data.
    string upperName = name.ToUpper(); 
    Console.WriteLine(upperName);
}
